				<div class="postbody">
				</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Insurance companies decide what they are willing to pay doctors, and it is illegal for the doctors to get together to decide whether to accept the bones they are being tossed or not. If 2 or more doctors reject an insurance company's offer, they get investigated for conspiracy. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
This is actually incorrect.   Most Doctors belong to a PA (Physican Association) that engages in negotiations with the various insurance plans.   Often times the Physicans cannot come to agreement and pull out of a plan.    The plan I operate lost its biggest hospital system (the Memorial Herman system if you happen to be familiar with Houston) because a agreement of terms could not be agreed upon.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I have no idea how to construct a system that would work well, but it'd be nice if the poor had access to decent healthcare without bogging down the emergency rooms. The cost of "free" emergency room care gets passed onto the public anyway, so I'd rather see them be able to get treatment in regular clinics, thus freeing up emergency rooms for the more serious stuff and lowering costs for everyone. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
This is accurate and a major problem.   Close to 35% of public hospital expenses generated in this country go without either billing or payment because the patient has no money.    This is either passed on to medicare or to private insurance carriers (either way, the working man/woman pays the bill).    Most clinics, however, are private enterprises who are in business to earn a profit.    While it would be nice if some system could be established so that they could be paid for services, they cant be expected to provide free services.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">My local newspaper did a big story on the life of one of our street people. He's a chronic alcoholic. The cops will find him comatose on the sidewalk and haul him off to the hospital. This happens frequently. The bill to the taxpayers in one year? Roughly one million dollars. Every time they fix him up, he goes back out onto the streets and gets wasted. Hell's bells, if the government paid him $100,000 a year to stay sober, it'd be a bargain. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
My answer would to be to attempt to resolve his problem once, then let him do as he pleases.   If he chooses to die because of his personal choices, he has the freedom to do that.     Point is that our medical system is barely 100 years old, the first Blue Cross Blue Shield plan was a cooperative effort started in Dallas and cost local teachers 50 cents a month to participate.    What did people do before that?   Easy, they just didnt live as long.     I see "long life" as a nice incentive to work hard and have provide yourself with proper medical care.   Capitalism at its finest.
<br />

<br />
The biggest issue with our medical system is not the insurance companies, it is not the Doctors, it is not the Hospitals,  IT IS the consumer.    When is the last time you checked prices on a surgery or doctor visit?    People will spend 4 days checking out every internet site in the world for the best price on a hard drive but dont compare a single price when having their toncils removed.
<br />

<br />
Ever wonder why laser eye surgery continues to get cheaper and higher quality?   Because the people that have that done are paying for it out of their pocket and the price matters.<br />
