			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Being a Canadian, and living so close to three American border crossings, I feel that this argument hits kinda close to home.  I think the biggest dilemma facing the Canadian health care system right now is a lack of direction for the future.  
<br />

<br />
Everyone is aware of the huge cost associated with running a national healthcare system, but just throwing money at the situation will not fix it.  Healthcare has always had the potential to be a black hole that politicans can just throw huge sums of money in to appease the masses, without ever really addressing the concerns facing the program.  The Romanow report tried to accomplish just that, and did lay out some plans for how the system needs to be revised/modified in order to deal with the current state of national health.  
<br />

<br />
While I am aware of the increasing number of Canadians that travel south for MRI's and other procedures, I am wholeheartedly against privatization of the healthcare system.  While we cannot stop people from choosing where they wish to spend their money, we can play an active role in providing services to people who do not have as much freedom with the money they have.  
<br />

<br />
Wealthy people will always be able to fly to wherever they want and get procedures done immediately, its the nature of the consumer-driven system that's in place in the US.  I am not here to laud the Canadian system, or bash the US system, because personally I believe that each country has adopted the system that best suits the needs of their individual populations.  While it may be feasible to provide 30 million Canadians with healthcare, a similar system may not work if were needed to supply healthcare to 300 million Americans.  
<br />

<br />
What I am here to say is that the Canadian system provides more than adequate coverage and service for our population, and has done so since its inception.  Patients are becoming more impatient these days, and as a result, they are over-using the system and creating longer lineups and backlogs.  If parents had to pay for visits to the doctor, maybe they wouldnt head to the emergency room every time their baby coughs.  Or maybe they wouldnt see 3 doctors in a row looking for the diagnosis that makes them feel the best.  We Canadians need to accept the limitations of the system that is provided for us, and start treating it with respect.  If everyone just did their part in trying to curb over-use, the medical professionals we have would be more readily available when we really need them.
<br />

<br />
Meletus v1.0
<br />
Retired 65 dr00d<br />
