			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Notice that their first reaction to a problem is get more money...
<br />

<br />
###
<br />

<br />
Try privatization!
<br />

<br />
Its really kewl.
<br />

<br />
You see doctors that SUCK to to work in McDonalds because no one is ever forced to see them. Patients also take much better responsibility for their own health when they have to think about the money they pay to fix it.
<br />

<br />
So many other benefits like negotiating with your own doctors. Not being made to feel like a greedy and ungrateful schmuck when you try to get to a real doctor instead of a candy striper; Recourse if you get screwed up by a scheister; You even have access to experimental and cutting edge treatments in a free market. I guess Canadians are aware of this though... they keep coming to the US to get procedures done that they cannot get at home.
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
In Canada, we are not assigned a Doctor, we pick one who is currently taking new patients and if we like them, we stick with them.  Doctors who suck either get an unending stream of new patients who didn't know any better (in larger cities) or eventually have no patients (cities small enough that word gets around, yet large enough to have a choice.  Occasionally they find a small town with no other doctor and people there are stuck with them until they can find a better one or they lose their license.
<br />

<br />
As far as what determines a right, this is a complex question that can have multiple answers.
<br />

<br />
I could define a right as anything I can enforce with my own strength of arms, intelligence and ability to communicate with my felllows.
<br />

<br />
I could define a right as anything defined in the US constitution or the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms.
<br />

<br />
I could list what is in the Bible, the Khoran, the Vedas or the Book of Urantia.
<br />

<br />
What a right really comes down to in a democratic society is what you can convince enough of your fellows should be a right that you can get it enshrined in law (and come up with a system to enforce).  The argument that public education should not be publicly funded will not fly as long as most people are convinced that it should be a 'right'.  Same thing goes for public health care.  To institute it, you need a majority who favor it.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
